ituencies/|title=Constituencies {{!}} Gaya {{!}} India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.electionsinindia.com/bihar/barachatti-assembly-vidhan-sabha-constituency-elections|title=Barachatti (SC) Vidhan Sabha Election - Barachatti (SC) Assembly Election Results, Polling Stations, Voters, Candidates|website=www.electionsinindia.com|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Assembly constituencies of Bihar]]\n", "name_user": "GargAvinash", "label": "safe", "comment": "+{{Bihar-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barachatti_(Vidhan_Sabha_constituency)"}
{"title_page": "Law Preview", "text_new": "'''Law Preview''' is a member of The BARBRI Group - the country's leading legal education provider -- and offers a 5- or 6-day law school prep course, designed to prepare entering law students for law school.<ref>[http://www.lawpreview.com Law Preview - Law School Prep Course & Law School Preview Class<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n\nThe course introduces the six core [[law school]] courses that most students encounter in their first year - [[torts]], [[civil procedure]], [[contracts]], [[property]], [[criminal law]] and legal research and writing. Each day of the course is devoted to one first-year subject and prominent professors are brought in from law schools across the country, including [[Dan Kahan]] from [[Yale Law School]] and [[G Marcus Cole]] from [[Stanford Law School]].<ref>https://lawpreview.barbri.com/course-information/faculty/</ref> The company advertises a 99% satisfaction rate and has a page devoted to alumni testimonials by law school that are unsolicited.\n\nLaw Preview has also teamed up with some leading BigLaw firms (and top law schools) to offer scholarships for diverse students matriculating at select law schools.<ref>http://www.lawpreview.com/scholarships</ref>\n\n== Locations ==\nLaw Preview offers live classroom programs in law schools across the United States: [[Atlanta]], [[Austin, Texas]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]], [[Dayton]], [[Dallas/Fort Worth]], [[Houston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], [[Philadelphia]], [[San Francisco]] and [[Washington, D.C.]]. Several larger locations such as New York, Los Angeles and Washington D.C. offer several sessions each. Though the time frame changes slightly each year, the Law Preview courses generally run from late June to late August. To accommodate students who are unable to travel, Law Preview offers Live Stream and On-Demand online courses as well.\n\n''Law School Confidential'' by Robert H. Miller says, \"Law Preview provides an excellent, long overdue product. Taking the one-week bootcamp cannot help but put you miles ahead of your uninitiated competition.\" The course has also appeared in The Law School Survival Guide by the editors of JD Jungle.\n\n== Websites ==\n\nThe owners of Law Preview also own and operate [http://www.barbri.com BARBRI Bar Review], as well as [http://www.admissionsdean.com AdmissionsDean.com], a social networking site for law school applicants that allows prospective applicants to track specific law schools (and specific applicants) to see who's getting into which schools so that they can better assess their own admissions chances.  In 2018, Law Preview launched the [http://jobnetwork.lawpreview.com Law Preview Job Network] - a free employment website that connects law students with legal recruiters.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n{{cite book |author=Miller, Robert Keith |title=Law school confidential: a complete guide to the law school experience: by students, for students |publisher=St. Martin's Griffin |location=New York |year=2004 |pages= |isbn=0-312-31881-2 |oclc= |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lawschoolconfide00mill }} \n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lawbooksforless.com LawBooksForLess.com]\n* [http://www.admissionsdean.com AdmissionsDean.com]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Massachusetts]]\n\n{{US-law-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Law Preview''' is a member of The BARBRI Group - the country's leading legal education provider -- and offers a 5- or 6-day law school prep course, designed to prepare entering law students for law school.<ref>[http://www.lawpreview.com Law Preview - Law School Prep Course & Law School Preview Class<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n\nThe course introduces the six core [[law school]] courses that most students encounter in their first year - [[torts]], [[civil procedure]], [[contracts]], [[property]], [[criminal law]] and legal research and writing. Each day of the course is devoted to one first-year subject and prominent professors are brought in from law schools across the country, including [[Dan Kahan]] from [[Yale Law School]] and [[G Marcus Cole]] from [[Stanford Law School]].<ref>https://lawpreview.barbri.com/course-information/faculty/</ref> The company advertises a 99% satisfaction rate and has a page devoted to alumni testimonials by law school that are unsolicited.\n\nLaw Preview has also teamed up with some leading BigLaw firms (and top law schools) to offer scholarships for diverse students matriculating at select law schools.<ref>http://www.lawpreview.com/scholarships</ref>\n\n== Locations ==\nLaw Preview offers live classroom programs in law schools across the United States: [[Atlanta]], [[Austin, Texas]], [[Boston]], [[Chicago]], [[Dayton]], [[Dallas/Fort Worth]], [[Houston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], [[Philadelphia]], [[San Francisco]] and [[Washington, D.C.]]. Several larger locations such as New York, Los Angeles and Washington D.C. offer several sessions each. Though the time frame changes slightly each year, the Law Preview courses generally run from late June to late August. To accommodate students who are unable to travel, Law Preview offers Live Stream and On-Demand online courses as well.\n\n''Law School Confidential'' by Robert H. Miller says, \"Law Preview provides an excellent, long overdue product. Taking the one-week bootcamp cannot help but put you miles ahead of your uninitiated competition.\" The course has also appeared in The Law School Survival Guide by the editors of JD Jungle.\n\n== Websites ==\n\nThe owners of Law Preview also own and operate [http://www.barbri.com BARBRI Bar Review], as well as [http://www.admissionsdean.com AdmissionsDean.com], a social networking site for law school applicants that allows prospective applicants to track specific law schools (and specific applicants) to see who\u2019s getting into which schools so that they can better assess their own admissions chances.  In 2018, Law Preview launched the [http://jobnetwork.lawpreview.com Law Preview Job Network] - a free employment website that connects law students with legal recruiters.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n{{cite book |author=Miller, Robert Keith |title=Law school confidential: a complete guide to the law school experience: by students, for students |publisher=St. Martin's Griffin |location=New York |year=2004 |pages= |isbn=0-312-31881-2 |oclc= |doi= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lawschoolconfide00mill }} \n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lawbooksforless.com LawBooksForLess.com]\n* [http://www.admissionsdean.com AdmissionsDean.com]\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Massachusetts]]\n\n{{US-law-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWebsites:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: who\u2019s \u2192 who's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_Preview"}
{"title_page": "Swordfish", "text_new": "{{About|a type of fish}}\n{{short description|The fish Xiphias gladius, which has a long, pointed bill}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Swordfish\n| fossil_range = {{fossilrange|3|0}} Early [[Pliocene]] to Present<ref name=fierstine>Fierstine, Harry L. \"A paleontological review of three billfish families (Istiophoridae, Xiphiidae, and Xiphiorhynchidae).\" Biological Sciences (1990): 11.</ref>\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn |\n author1 = Acero, A. | author2 = Amorim, A.F. | author3 = Bizsel, K. | author4 = Boustany, A. | author5 = Canales Ramirez, C. | author6 = Cardenas, G. | author7 = Carpenter, K.E. | author8 = de Oliveira Leite Jr., N. | author9 = Di Natale, A. | display-authors = etal | title = ''Xiphias gladius'' | volume = 2011 | page = e.T23148A88828055 | date = 2011 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2011-2.RLTS.T23148A9422329.en }}</ref>\n| image = Xiphias gladius2.jpg\n| grandparent_authority = [[William John Swainson|Swainson]], 1839 \n| genus = Xiphias\n| parent_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| species = gladius\n| display_parents = 3\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| range_map = World distribution Swordfish.svg\n| range_map_caption = Global distribution of swordfish in blue\n| synonyms = *''Xiphias imperator'' <small>[[Marcus Elieser Bloch|Bloch]] & [[Johann Gottlob Theaenus Schneider|Schneider]], 1801</small> \n*''Tetrapterus imperator'' <small>(Bloch & Schneider, 1801)</small> \n*''Xiphias rondeletii'' [[William Elford Leach|Leach]], 1814 \n*''Phaethonichthys tuberculatus'' <small>[[John Treadwell Nichols|Nichols]], 1923</small> \n*''Xiphias estara'' <small>Phillipps, 1932</small> \n*''Xiphias thermaicus'' <small>Serbetis, 1951</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name = FishBase>{{FishBase|Xiphias|gladius|month=February|year=2018}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''Swordfish''' (''Xiphias gladius''), also known as '''broadbills''' in some countries, are large, [[highly migratory]], [[predatory fish]] characterized by a long, flat, pointed bill. They are a popular sport fish of the [[billfish]] category, though elusive. Swordfish are elongated, round-bodied, and lose all teeth and scales by adulthood. These fish are found widely in tropical and temperate parts of the [[Atlantic]], [[Pacific]], and [[Indian Ocean]]s, and can typically be found from near the surface to a depth of {{convert|550|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IUCN/> They commonly reach {{convert|3|m|abbr=on}} in length, and the maximum reported is {{convert|4.55|m|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|650|kg|abbr=on}} in weight.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida>Gardieff, S. ''[http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/fish/Gallery/Descript/Swordfish/Swordfish.html Swordfish.]'' Florida Museum of Natural History. Accessed 26 December 2011</ref>\n\nThey are the sole member of their [[Family (biology)|family]], '''Xiphiidae'''.<ref>{{FishBase family | family = Xiphiidae | month = December | year = 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy and etymology==\nThe swordfish is named after its pointed, flat bill, which resembles a [[sword]].  The species name, ''Xiphias gladius'', derives from [[Greek Language|Greek]] {{wiktgrc|\u03be\u03b9\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}} (''xiphias'', \"swordfish\"), itself from {{wiktgrc|\u03be\u03af\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2}} (''xiphos'', \"sword\") and from [[Latin language|Latin]] {{wiktlat|gladius}} (\"sword\").<ref name=Florida/> This makes it superficially similar to other [[billfish]] such as [[marlin]], but upon examination, their physiology is quite different and they are members of different families.<ref>Pepperell, J. 2010. ''Fishes of the Open Ocean: A Natural History and Illustrated Guide.'' {{ISBN|978-0-226-65539-0}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThey commonly reach {{convert|3|m|abbr=on}} in length, and the maximum reported is {{convert|4.55|m|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|650|kg|abbr=on}} in weight.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida/> The [[International Game Fish Association]]'s all-tackle angling record for a swordfish was a {{convert|1182|lb|abbr=on|order=flip}} specimen taken off [[Chile]] in 1953.<ref name=IUCN/> Females are larger than males, and Pacific swordfish reach a greater size than northwest Atlantic and [[Mediterranean]] swordfish.<ref name=Florida/> They reach maturity at 4\u20135 years of age and the maximum age is believed to be at least 9 years.<ref name=Florida/> The oldest swordfish found in a recent study were a 16-year-old female and 12-year-old male. Swordfish ages are derived, with difficulty, from annual rings on fin rays rather than [[otolith]]s, since their otoliths are small in size.<ref>Jesse Marsh, Margot Stiles, 2007. \"Seafood Watch, Seafood Report, Monterey Bay Aquarium, [http://safinacenter.org/documents/2014/06/swordfish-seafood-watch-species-report.pdf]\"</ref>Big pp\n\nSwordfish are [[ectotherm]]ic animals; however, along with some species of [[shark]]s, they have special organs next to their [[eye]]s to heat their eyes and brains. Temperatures of {{convert|10|to|15|C-change|abbr=on}} above the surrounding water temperature have been measured.  The heating of the eyes greatly improves their [[Visual perception|vision]], and consequently improves their ability to catch prey.<ref name=warmeye1>Fritsches, K.A., Brill, R.W., and Warrant, E.J. 2005. ''[http://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(04)00996-0 Warm Eyes Provide Superior Vision in Swordfishes.]'' Current Biology 15: 55\u201358</ref><ref name=warmeye2>Hopkin, M. (2005). ''[http://www.nature.com/news/2005/050110/full/050110-2.html Swordfish heat their eyes for better vision.]'' Nature, 10 January 2005</ref> Of the 25 000+ fish species, only 22 are known to have a mechanism to conserve heat. These include the swordfish, [[marlin]], [[tuna]], and some sharks.<ref name=warmeye1/><ref name=warmeye2/>\n\n== Behavior and ecology ==\n[[File:Swordfish skeleton.jpg|thumb|350px|left|Swordfish skeleton at the [[National Museum of Natural History]], [[Washington, DC]]]]\n\nContrary to popular belief, the \"sword\" is not used to spear, but instead may be used to slash at its prey to injure the prey animal, to make for an easier catch.<ref name=Florida/>  Mainly, the swordfish relies on its great speed and agility in the water to catch its prey. It is no doubt among the fastest fish, but the basis for the frequently quoted speed of {{convert|60|mph|abbr=on|order=flip}} is unreliable.<ref name=speed>ReefQuest Centre for Shark Research. ''[http://www.elasmo-research.org/education/topics/r_haulin'_bass.htm Haulin' Bass.]'' Quote: ''\"The 60 mph figure listed for the swordfish is based on a corrupted version of calculations made by Sir James Gray to estimate the impact speed necessary for a hypothetical 600-lb swordfish to embed its sword 3 feet in the timbers of ships, as has been known to occur; the figure seems to have entered the literature without question.\"'' Accessed 26 December 2011.</ref>\n\nSwordfish prefer water temperatures between {{convert|18|and|22|C|abbr=on}},<ref name=IUCN/> but have the widest tolerance among [[billfish]], and can be found from {{convert|5|to|27|C|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Florida/> This highly migratory species typically moves towards colder regions to feed during the summer.<ref name=Florida/> Swordfish feed daily, most often at night, when they rise to surface and near-surface waters in search of smaller fish. During the day, they commonly occur to depths of {{convert|550|m|abbr=on}} and have exceptionally been recorded as deep as {{convert|2878|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IUCN/> Adults feed on a wide range of [[pelagic fish]], such as [[mackerel]], [[barracudina]]s, [[silver hake]], [[Sebastes|rockfish]], [[herring]], and [[lanternfish]]es, but they also take [[demersal fish]], [[squid]], and [[crustacean]]s.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida/> In the northwestern Atlantic, a survey based on the stomach content of 168 individuals found 82% had eaten squid and 53% had eaten fish, including [[Gadidae|gadids]], [[scombrid]]s, [[butterfish]], [[bluefish]], and [[sand lance]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Stillwell | last2 = Kohler | year = 1985 | title = Food and feeding ecology of the swordfish Xiphias gladius in the western North Atlantic Ocean with estimates of daily ration | journal = Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser. | volume = 22 | issue = | pages = 239\u2013241 | doi=10.3354/meps022239| bibcode = 1985MEPS...22..239S }}</ref> Large prey are typically slashed with the sword, while small are swallowed whole.<ref name=Florida/>\n\n[[File:Swordfish-0046.jpg|thumb|350px|Stuffed broadbill swordfish]]\nSwordfish are not [[Shoaling and schooling|schooling]] fish. They swim alone or in very loose aggregations, separated by as much as {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}} from a neighboring swordfish. They are frequently found basking at the surface, airing their first dorsal fin. Boaters report this to be a beautiful sight, as is the powerful jumping for which the species is known. This jumping, also called breaching, may be an effort to dislodge pests, such as [[remora]]s or [[lampreys]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n \nAlmost 50 species of [[Parasitism|parasites]] have been documented in swordfish. In addition to remoras, lampreys, and [[cookiecutter shark]]s, this includes a wide range of invertebrates, such as [[tapeworm]]s, [[roundworm]]s, and [[copepod]]s.<ref name=Florida/> A comparison of the parasites of swordfish in the [[Atlantic]] and in the [[Mediterranean]] indicated that some parasites, particularly [[Anisakis]] spp. larvae identified by genetic markers, could be used as biological tags and support the existence of a Mediterranean swordfish [[Fish stock|stock]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mattiucci | first1 = S. | last2 = Garcia | first2 = A. | last3 = Cipriani | first3 = P. | last4 = Santos | first4 = M. N. | last5 = Nascetti | first5 = G. | last6 = Cimmaruta | first6 = R. | year = 2014 | title = Metazoan parasite infection in the swordfish, ''Xiphias gladius'', from the Mediterranean Sea and comparison with Atlantic populations: implications for its stock characterization | journal = Parasite | volume = 21 | issue = | page = 35 | doi = 10.1051/parasite/2014036 | pmid = 25057787 | pmc=4109596}}</ref>\n\nFully adult swordfish have few natural predators. Among marine mammals, [[killer whale]]s sometimes prey on adult swordfish.<ref name=Florida/> The [[shortfin mako]], an exceptionally fast species of shark, sometimes take on swordfish; dead or dying shortfin makos have been found with broken-off swords in their heads, revealing the danger of this type of prey.<ref name=mako>The Shark Trust. {{cite web |url=http://sharks-med.netfirms.com/med/mako.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714165639/http://sharks-med.netfirms.com/med/mako.htm |archivedate=2011-07-14 |title=Shortfin mako|accessdate=2011-12-26 }}</ref> Juvenile swordfish are far more vulnerable to predation,  and are eaten by a wide range of predatory fish.<ref name=Florida/>\n\n=== Breeding ===\nIn the North Pacific, batch spawning mainly occurs in water warmer than {{convert|24|C|abbr=on}} during the spring and summer, and year-round in the equatorial Pacific.<ref name=IUCN/> In the North Atlantic, spawning is known from the [[Sargasso Sea]],<ref name=fishbase>{{FishBase | genus = Xiphias | species = gladius | month = December | year = 2011}}</ref> and in water warmer than {{convert|23|C|abbr=on}} and less than {{convert|75|m|abbr=on}} deep.<ref name=IUCN/> Spawning occurs from November to February in the South Atlantic off southern [[Brazil]].<ref name=IUCN/> Spawning is year-round in the [[Caribbean Sea]] and other warm regions of the west Atlantic.<ref name=Florida/>\n\nLarge females can carry more eggs than small females, and between 1 million to 29 million eggs have been recorded.<ref name=IUCN/> The pelagic eggs measure {{convert|1.6|-|1.8|mm|abbr=on}} in diameter and 2.5 days after fertilization, the embryonic development occurs.<ref name=fishbase/><ref name=Florida/> The surface-living and unique-looking larvae are {{convert|4|mm|abbr=on}} long at hatching.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida/> The bill is evident when the larvae reach {{convert|1|cm|abbr=on|1}} in length.<ref name=FishBase/>\n\n==Fisheries==\n[[File:Barca pescespada 3.jpg|thumb|180px|left|[[Felucca]] used in the [[Strait of Messina]] to hunt swordfish]]\n[[File:Fisheries capture of Xiphias gladius.png|thumb|400px|right|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Global capture of swordfish in tonnes reported by the [[FAO]], 1950\u20132009<ref name=FAOdata>Based on data sourced from the relevant [http://www.fao.org/fishery/species/search/en FAO Species Fact Sheets]</ref></div>]]\n\nSwordfish were harvested by a variety of methods at small scale (notably [[harpoon]] fishing) until the global expansion of [[long-line fishing]]. They have been fished widely since ancient times in places such as the [[Strait of Messina]], where they are still fished with traditional wooden boats called [[felucca]]s and are part of the cuisine in that area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuke.prolocobagnara.it/BagnaraCalabra/Storia/LaPesca/LaPescadelPescespada/tabid/495/Default.aspx |title=La Pesca del Pescespada  |access-date=2011-12-30 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081914/http://nuke.prolocobagnara.it/BagnaraCalabra/Storia/LaPesca/LaPescadelPescespada/tabid/495/Default.aspx |archive-date=2012-04-26 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biologiamarina.eu/PesceSpada.html|title=La pesca del pesce spada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ganzirri.it/spip.php?article9|title=La tecnica per la pesca del pescespada e la \"Feluca\" \u2013 [Ganzirri, il Peloro e lo Stretto di Messina]}}</ref>\n\nSwordfish are vigorous, powerful fighters. When hooked or harpooned, they have been known to dive so quickly, they have impaled their swords into the ocean bottom up to their eyes. Although no unprovoked attacks on humans have been reported, swordfish can be very dangerous when harpooned. They have run their swords through the planking of small boats when hurt. In 2015, a Hawaiian fisherman was killed by a swordfish after attempting to spear the animal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swordfish kills fisherman in Hawaii|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/30/us/hawaii-swordfish-kills-fisherman|publisher=CNN.com|last2=Marco|first2=Tony|last1=Preuss|first1=Andreas|date=2015-06-01}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Recreational fishing ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=February 2010}}\nRecreational fishing has developed a subspecialty called swordfishing. Because of a ban on long-lining along many parts of seashore, swordfish populations are showing signs of recovery from the [[overfishing]] caused by long-lining along the coast.\n\nVarious ways are used to fish for swordfish, but the most common method is deep-drop fishing, since swordfish spend most daylight hours very deep, in the [[deep scattering layer]]. The boat is allowed to drift to present a more natural bait. Swordfishing requires strong fishing rods and reels, as swordfish can become quite large, and it is not uncommon to use five pounds or more of weight to get the baits deep enough during the day, up to 1,500&nbsp;feet is common.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fishingbooker.com/blog/proven-daytime-swordfish-tactics|title=Daytime Swordfish Tactics That Work Like a Charm|work=FishingBooker.com|date=2018-10-13}}</ref> Night fishing baits are usually fished much shallower, often less than {{convert|90|m}}. Standard baits are whole mackerel, herring, mullet, bonito, or squid; one can also use live bait. Imitation squids and other imitation fish lures can also be used, and specialized lures made specifically for swordfishing often have battery-powered or glow lights. Even baits are typically presented using glow sticks or specialized deepwater-proof battery operated lights.\n\n== As food ==\n\n{{See also|Mercury in fish}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Marinated grill swordfish.jpeg|[[Marination|Marinated]] swordfish\nFile:Fried Swordfish collar.jpg|Fried swordfish collars\nFile:Swordfish in Limnionas, Kos, Greece (5653643083).jpg|Swordfish dish in [[Kos]]\n</gallery>\nSwordfish are classified as [[oily fish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.food.gov.uk/news/newsarchive/2004/jun/oilyfishdefinition|title=What's an oily fish?|date=24 June 2004|publisher=[[Food Standards Agency]]}}</ref> Many sources, including the [[United States Food and Drug Administration]], warn about potential toxicity from high levels of [[methylmercury]] in swordfish.<ref name=\"Mercury Levels in Commercial Fish and Shellfish\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115644.htm\n|title=Mercury Levels in Commercial Fish and Shellfish\n|author=FDA\n|date=1990\u20132010\n|accessdate=2011-09-14}}\n</ref><ref name=\"What you need to know about mercury in fish and shellfish\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.epa.gov/waterscience/fishadvice/advice.html#isthere\n|title=What you need to know about mercury in fish and shellfish\n|author=EPA\n|accessdate=2011-09-14}}\n</ref> The FDA recommends that young children, pregnant women, and women of child-bearing age not eat swordfish.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fda.gov/media/102331/download|title=Advice About Eating Fish|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=2019-09-27|author=FDA|publisher=[[FDA]]}}</ref>\n\nThe flesh of some swordfish can acquire an orange tint, reportedly from their diet of shrimp or other prey. Such fish are sold as \"pumpkin swordfish\", and command a premium over their whitish counterparts.<!-- (Information from U.S. vendor [[Whole Foods Market|Whole Foods]].)-->\n\nSwordfish is a particularly popular fish for cooking. Since swordfish are large, meat is usually sold as steaks, which are often [[grilled]]. Swordfish meat is relatively firm, and can be cooked in ways more fragile types of fish cannot (such as over a grill on skewers). The color of the flesh varies by diet, with fish caught on the East Coast of [[North America]] often being rosier.\n\n== Conservation status ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2011}}\n[[File:Xiphias gladius.jpg|thumb|Swordfish on deck during long-lining operations]]\nIn 1998, the US [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and [[SeaWeb]] hired [[Fenton Communications]] to conduct an advertising campaign to promote their assertion that the swordfish population was in danger due to its popularity as a restaurant entree.<ref>[http://www.fenton.com/pages/3_ourwork/4_casestudies/environment/swordfish.htm Swordfish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231113316/http://www.fenton.com/pages/3_ourwork/4_casestudies/environment/swordfish.htm |date=2007-12-31 }} Fenton Communications</ref>\n\nThe resulting \"Give Swordfish a Break\" promotion was wildly successful, with 750 prominent US chefs agreeing to remove North Atlantic swordfish from their menus, and also persuaded many supermarkets and consumers across the country.\n\nThe advertising campaign was repeated by the national media in hundreds of print and broadcast stories, as well as extensive regional coverage. It earned the [[Silver Anvil award]] from the Public Relations Society of America, as well as'' Time'' magazine's award for the top five environmental stories of 1998.\n\nSubsequently, the US [[National Marine Fisheries Service]] proposed a swordfish protection plan that incorporated the campaign's policy suggestions. [[President of the United States of America|Then-US President]] [[Bill Clinton]] called for a ban on the sale and import of swordfish and in a landmark decision by the federal government, {{convert|132670|sqmi|km2|abbr=on}} of the Atlantic Ocean were placed off-limits to fishing as recommended by the sponsors.\n\nIn the North Atlantic, the swordfish stock is fully rebuilt, with biomass estimates currently 5% above the target level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/fishwatch/species/n_atl_swordfish.htm|title=FishWatch}}</ref> No robust stock assessments for swordfish in the northwestern Pacific or South Atlantic have been made, and data concerning stock status in these regions are lacking. These stocks are considered unknown and a moderate conservation concern. The southwestern Pacific stock is a moderate concern due to model uncertainty, increasing catches, and declining [[catch per unit effort]]. Overfishing is likely occurring in the Indian Ocean, and fishing mortality exceeds the maximum recommended level in the Mediterranean, thus these stocks are considered of high conservation concern.<ref>[http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/content/media/MBA_SeafoodWatch_SwordfishReport.pdf Seafood Watch \u2013 Seafood Report \u2013 Swordfish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714231946/http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/content/media/MBA_SeafoodWatch_SwordfishReport.pdf |date=2007-07-14 }} Monterey Bay Aquarium, 16 July 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Greenpeace International]] added the swordfish to its seafood red list.<!-- \"The Greenpeace International seafood red list is a list of fish that are commonly sold in supermarkets around the world, and which have a very high risk of being sourced from unsustainable fisheries.\"--><ref>{{cite web|title=Greenpeace International Seafood Red List|url=http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/campaigns/oceans/seafood/red-list-of-species/|accessdate=14 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==In culture==\n*The swordfish (''Xiphias'') has been used by astronomers as another name for the constellation of [[Dorado]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n== Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Swordfish: A Biography of the Ocean Gladiator |author=Richard Ellis |year=2013 |isbn=978-0226922904}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Xiphiidae}}\n{{Wikispecies|Xiphias gladius}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070714231946/http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/content/media/MBA_SeafoodWatch_SwordfishReport.pdf Swordfish, Seafood Watch, Monterey Bay Aquarium]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050420075231/https://www.fda.gov/fdac/reprints/mercury.html FDA Consumer:Mercury In Fish:Cause For Concern?]\n\n{{billfish|state=autocollapse}}\n{{commercial fish topics|start=autocollapse}}\n{{Meat|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q164327}}\n\n[[Category:Xiphiidae| ]]\n[[Category:Cosmopolitan fish]]\n[[Category:Oily fish]]\n[[Category:Sport fish]]\n[[Category:Hawaiian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Greek cuisine]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1758]]\n[[Category:Extant Pliocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a type of fish}}\n{{short description|The fish Xiphias gladius, which has a long, pointed bill}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Swordfish\n| fossil_range = {{fossilrange|3|0}} Early [[Pliocene]] to Present<ref name=fierstine>Fierstine, Harry L. \"A paleontological review of three billfish families (Istiophoridae, Xiphiidae, and Xiphiorhynchidae).\" Biological Sciences (1990): 11.</ref>\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn |\n author1 = Acero, A. | author2 = Amorim, A.F. | author3 = Bizsel, K. | author4 = Boustany, A. | author5 = Canales Ramirez, C. | author6 = Cardenas, G. | author7 = Carpenter, K.E. | author8 = de Oliveira Leite Jr., N. | author9 = Di Natale, A. | display-authors = etal | title = ''Xiphias gladius'' | volume = 2011 | page = e.T23148A88828055 | date = 2011 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2011-2.RLTS.T23148A9422329.en }}</ref>\n| image = Xiphias gladius2.jpg\n| grandparent_authority = [[William John Swainson|Swainson]], 1839 \n| genus = Xiphias\n| parent_authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| species = gladius\n| display_parents = 3\n| authority = [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]]\n| range_map = World distribution Swordfish.svg\n| range_map_caption = Global distribution of swordfish in blue\n| synonyms = *''Xiphias imperator'' <small>[[Marcus Elieser Bloch|Bloch]] & [[Johann Gottlob Theaenus Schneider|Schneider]], 1801</small> \n*''Tetrapterus imperator'' <small>(Bloch & Schneider, 1801)</small> \n*''Xiphias rondeletii'' [[William Elford Leach|Leach]], 1814 \n*''Phaethonichthys tuberculatus'' <small>[[John Treadwell Nichols|Nichols]], 1923</small> \n*''Xiphias estara'' <small>Phillipps, 1932</small> \n*''Xiphias thermaicus'' <small>Serbetis, 1951</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name = FishBase>{{FishBase|Xiphias|gladius|month=February|year=2018}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''Swordfish''' (''Xiphias gladius''), also known as '''broadbills''' in some countries, are large, [[highly migratory]], [[predatory fish]] characterized by a long, flat, pointed bill. They are a popular sport fish of the [[billfish]] category, though elusive. Swordfish are elongated, round-bodied, and lose all teeth and scales by adulthood. These fish are found widely in tropical and temperate parts of the [[Atlantic]], [[Pacific]], and [[Indian Ocean]]s, and can typically be found from near the surface to a depth of {{convert|550|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IUCN/> They commonly reach {{convert|3|m|abbr=on}} in length, and the maximum reported is {{convert|4.55|m|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|650|kg|abbr=on}} in weight.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida>Gardieff, S. ''[http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/fish/Gallery/Descript/Swordfish/Swordfish.html Swordfish.]'' Florida Museum of Natural History. Accessed 26 December 2011</ref>\n\nThey are the sole member of their [[Family (biology)|family]], '''Xiphiidae'''.<ref>{{FishBase family | family = Xiphiidae | month = December | year = 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy and etymology==\nThe swordfish is named after its pointed, flat bill, which resembles a [[sword]].  The species name, ''Xiphias gladius'', derives from [[Greek Language|Greek]] {{wiktgrc|\u03be\u03b9\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}} (''xiphias'', \"swordfish\"), itself from {{wiktgrc|\u03be\u03af\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2}} (''xiphos'', \"sword\") and from [[Latin language|Latin]] {{wiktlat|gladius}} (\"sword\").<ref name=Florida/> This makes it superficially similar to other [[billfish]] such as [[marlin]], but upon examination, their physiology is quite different and they are members of different families.<ref>Pepperell, J. 2010. ''Fishes of the Open Ocean: A Natural History and Illustrated Guide.'' {{ISBN|978-0-226-65539-0}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThey commonly reach {{convert|3|m|abbr=on}} in length, and the maximum reported is {{convert|4.55|m|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|650|kg|abbr=on}} in weight.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida/> The [[International Game Fish Association]]'s all-tackle angling record for a swordfish was a {{convert|1182|lb|abbr=on|order=flip}} specimen taken off [[Chile]] in 1953.<ref name=IUCN/> Females are larger than males, and Pacific swordfish reach a greater size than northwest Atlantic and [[Mediterranean]] swordfish.<ref name=Florida/> They reach maturity at 4\u20135 years of age and the maximum age is believed to be at least 9 years.<ref name=Florida/> The oldest swordfish found in a recent study were a 16-year-old female and 12-year-old male. Swordfish ages are derived, with difficulty, from annual rings on fin rays rather than [[otolith]]s, since their otoliths are small in size.<ref>Jesse Marsh, Margot Stiles, 2007. \"Seafood Watch, Seafood Report, Monterey Bay Aquarium, [http://safinacenter.org/documents/2014/06/swordfish-seafood-watch-species-report.pdf]\"</ref>\n\nSwordfish are [[ectotherm]]ic animals; however, along with some species of [[shark]]s, they have special organs next to their [[eye]]s to heat their eyes and brains. Temperatures of {{convert|10|to|15|C-change|abbr=on}} above the surrounding water temperature have been measured.  The heating of the eyes greatly improves their [[Visual perception|vision]], and consequently improves their ability to catch prey.<ref name=warmeye1>Fritsches, K.A., Brill, R.W., and Warrant, E.J. 2005. ''[http://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(04)00996-0 Warm Eyes Provide Superior Vision in Swordfishes.]'' Current Biology 15: 55\u201358</ref><ref name=warmeye2>Hopkin, M. (2005). ''[http://www.nature.com/news/2005/050110/full/050110-2.html Swordfish heat their eyes for better vision.]'' Nature, 10 January 2005</ref> Of the 25 000+ fish species, only 22 are known to have a mechanism to conserve heat. These include the swordfish, [[marlin]], [[tuna]], and some sharks.<ref name=warmeye1/><ref name=warmeye2/>\n\n== Behavior and ecology ==\n[[File:Swordfish skeleton.jpg|thumb|350px|left|Swordfish skeleton at the [[National Museum of Natural History]], [[Washington, DC]]]]\n\nContrary to popular belief, the \"sword\" is not used to spear, but instead may be used to slash at its prey to injure the prey animal, to make for an easier catch.<ref name=Florida/>  Mainly, the swordfish relies on its great speed and agility in the water to catch its prey. It is no doubt among the fastest fish, but the basis for the frequently quoted speed of {{convert|60|mph|abbr=on|order=flip}} is unreliable.<ref name=speed>ReefQuest Centre for Shark Research. ''[http://www.elasmo-research.org/education/topics/r_haulin'_bass.htm Haulin' Bass.]'' Quote: ''\"The 60 mph figure listed for the swordfish is based on a corrupted version of calculations made by Sir James Gray to estimate the impact speed necessary for a hypothetical 600-lb swordfish to embed its sword 3 feet in the timbers of ships, as has been known to occur; the figure seems to have entered the literature without question.\"'' Accessed 26 December 2011.</ref>\n\nSwordfish prefer water temperatures between {{convert|18|and|22|C|abbr=on}},<ref name=IUCN/> but have the widest tolerance among [[billfish]], and can be found from {{convert|5|to|27|C|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Florida/> This highly migratory species typically moves towards colder regions to feed during the summer.<ref name=Florida/> Swordfish feed daily, most often at night, when they rise to surface and near-surface waters in search of smaller fish. During the day, they commonly occur to depths of {{convert|550|m|abbr=on}} and have exceptionally been recorded as deep as {{convert|2878|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=IUCN/> Adults feed on a wide range of [[pelagic fish]], such as [[mackerel]], [[barracudina]]s, [[silver hake]], [[Sebastes|rockfish]], [[herring]], and [[lanternfish]]es, but they also take [[demersal fish]], [[squid]], and [[crustacean]]s.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida/> In the northwestern Atlantic, a survey based on the stomach content of 168 individuals found 82% had eaten squid and 53% had eaten fish, including [[Gadidae|gadids]], [[scombrid]]s, [[butterfish]], [[bluefish]], and [[sand lance]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Stillwell | last2 = Kohler | year = 1985 | title = Food and feeding ecology of the swordfish Xiphias gladius in the western North Atlantic Ocean with estimates of daily ration | journal = Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser. | volume = 22 | issue = | pages = 239\u2013241 | doi=10.3354/meps022239| bibcode = 1985MEPS...22..239S }}</ref> Large prey are typically slashed with the sword, while small are swallowed whole.<ref name=Florida/>\n\n[[File:Swordfish-0046.jpg|thumb|350px|Stuffed broadbill swordfish]]\nSwordfish are not [[Shoaling and schooling|schooling]] fish. They swim alone or in very loose aggregations, separated by as much as {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}} from a neighboring swordfish. They are frequently found basking at the surface, airing their first dorsal fin. Boaters report this to be a beautiful sight, as is the powerful jumping for which the species is known. This jumping, also called breaching, may be an effort to dislodge pests, such as [[remora]]s or [[lampreys]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n \nAlmost 50 species of [[Parasitism|parasites]] have been documented in swordfish. In addition to remoras, lampreys, and [[cookiecutter shark]]s, this includes a wide range of invertebrates, such as [[tapeworm]]s, [[roundworm]]s, and [[copepod]]s.<ref name=Florida/> A comparison of the parasites of swordfish in the [[Atlantic]] and in the [[Mediterranean]] indicated that some parasites, particularly [[Anisakis]] spp. larvae identified by genetic markers, could be used as biological tags and support the existence of a Mediterranean swordfish [[Fish stock|stock]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mattiucci | first1 = S. | last2 = Garcia | first2 = A. | last3 = Cipriani | first3 = P. | last4 = Santos | first4 = M. N. | last5 = Nascetti | first5 = G. | last6 = Cimmaruta | first6 = R. | year = 2014 | title = Metazoan parasite infection in the swordfish, ''Xiphias gladius'', from the Mediterranean Sea and comparison with Atlantic populations: implications for its stock characterization | journal = Parasite | volume = 21 | issue = | page = 35 | doi = 10.1051/parasite/2014036 | pmid = 25057787 | pmc=4109596}}</ref>\n\nFully adult swordfish have few natural predators. Among marine mammals, [[killer whale]]s sometimes prey on adult swordfish.<ref name=Florida/> The [[shortfin mako]], an exceptionally fast species of shark, sometimes take on swordfish; dead or dying shortfin makos have been found with broken-off swords in their heads, revealing the danger of this type of prey.<ref name=mako>The Shark Trust. {{cite web |url=http://sharks-med.netfirms.com/med/mako.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714165639/http://sharks-med.netfirms.com/med/mako.htm |archivedate=2011-07-14 |title=Shortfin mako|accessdate=2011-12-26 }}</ref> Juvenile swordfish are far more vulnerable to predation,  and are eaten by a wide range of predatory fish.<ref name=Florida/>\n\n=== Breeding ===\nIn the North Pacific, batch spawning mainly occurs in water warmer than {{convert|24|C|abbr=on}} during the spring and summer, and year-round in the equatorial Pacific.<ref name=IUCN/> In the North Atlantic, spawning is known from the [[Sargasso Sea]],<ref name=fishbase>{{FishBase | genus = Xiphias | species = gladius | month = December | year = 2011}}</ref> and in water warmer than {{convert|23|C|abbr=on}} and less than {{convert|75|m|abbr=on}} deep.<ref name=IUCN/> Spawning occurs from November to February in the South Atlantic off southern [[Brazil]].<ref name=IUCN/> Spawning is year-round in the [[Caribbean Sea]] and other warm regions of the west Atlantic.<ref name=Florida/>\n\nLarge females can carry more eggs than small females, and between 1 million to 29 million eggs have been recorded.<ref name=IUCN/> The pelagic eggs measure {{convert|1.6|-|1.8|mm|abbr=on}} in diameter and 2.5 days after fertilization, the embryonic development occurs.<ref name=fishbase/><ref name=Florida/> The surface-living and unique-looking larvae are {{convert|4|mm|abbr=on}} long at hatching.<ref name=FishBase/><ref name=Florida/> The bill is evident when the larvae reach {{convert|1|cm|abbr=on|1}} in length.<ref name=FishBase/>\n\n==Fisheries==\n[[File:Barca pescespada 3.jpg|thumb|180px|left|[[Felucca]] used in the [[Strait of Messina]] to hunt swordfish]]\n[[File:Fisheries capture of Xiphias gladius.png|thumb|400px|right|<div style=\"text-align: center;\">Global capture of swordfish in tonnes reported by the [[FAO]], 1950\u20132009<ref name=FAOdata>Based on data sourced from the relevant [http://www.fao.org/fishery/species/search/en FAO Species Fact Sheets]</ref></div>]]\n\nSwordfish were harvested by a variety of methods at small scale (notably [[harpoon]] fishing) until the global expansion of [[long-line fishing]]. They have been fished widely since ancient times in places such as the [[Strait of Messina]], where they are still fished with traditional wooden boats called [[felucca]]s and are part of the cuisine in that area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuke.prolocobagnara.it/BagnaraCalabra/Storia/LaPesca/LaPescadelPescespada/tabid/495/Default.aspx |title=La Pesca del Pescespada  |access-date=2011-12-30 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426081914/http://nuke.prolocobagnara.it/BagnaraCalabra/Storia/LaPesca/LaPescadelPescespada/tabid/495/Default.aspx |archive-date=2012-04-26 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biologiamarina.eu/PesceSpada.html|title=La pesca del pesce spada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ganzirri.it/spip.php?article9|title=La tecnica per la pesca del pescespada e la \"Feluca\" \u2013 [Ganzirri, il Peloro e lo Stretto di Messina]}}</ref>\n\nSwordfish are vigorous, powerful fighters. When hooked or harpooned, they have been known to dive so quickly, they have impaled their swords into the ocean bottom up to their eyes. Although no unprovoked attacks on humans have been reported, swordfish can be very dangerous when harpooned. They have run their swords through the planking of small boats when hurt. In 2015, a Hawaiian fisherman was killed by a swordfish after attempting to spear the animal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Swordfish kills fisherman in Hawaii|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/30/us/hawaii-swordfish-kills-fisherman|publisher=CNN.com|last2=Marco|first2=Tony|last1=Preuss|first1=Andreas|date=2015-06-01}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Recreational fishing ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=February 2010}}\nRecreational fishing has developed a subspecialty called swordfishing. Because of a ban on long-lining along many parts of seashore, swordfish populations are showing signs of recovery from the [[overfishing]] caused by long-lining along the coast.\n\nVarious ways are used to fish for swordfish, but the most common method is deep-drop fishing, since swordfish spend most daylight hours very deep, in the [[deep scattering layer]]. The boat is allowed to drift to present a more natural bait. Swordfishing requires strong fishing rods and reels, as swordfish can become quite large, and it is not uncommon to use five pounds or more of weight to get the baits deep enough during the day, up to 1,500&nbsp;feet is common.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fishingbooker.com/blog/proven-daytime-swordfish-tactics|title=Daytime Swordfish Tactics That Work Like a Charm|work=FishingBooker.com|date=2018-10-13}}</ref> Night fishing baits are usually fished much shallower, often less than {{convert|90|m}}. Standard baits are whole mackerel, herring, mullet, bonito, or squid; one can also use live bait. Imitation squids and other imitation fish lures can also be used, and specialized lures made specifically for swordfishing often have battery-powered or glow lights. Even baits are typically presented using glow sticks or specialized deepwater-proof battery operated lights.\n\n== As food ==\n\n{{See also|Mercury in fish}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Marinated grill swordfish.jpeg|[[Marination|Marinated]] swordfish\nFile:Fried Swordfish collar.jpg|Fried swordfish collars\nFile:Swordfish in Limnionas, Kos, Greece (5653643083).jpg|Swordfish dish in [[Kos]]\n</gallery>\nSwordfish are classified as [[oily fish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.food.gov.uk/news/newsarchive/2004/jun/oilyfishdefinition|title=What's an oily fish?|date=24 June 2004|publisher=[[Food Standards Agency]]}}</ref> Many sources, including the [[United States Food and Drug Administration]], warn about potential toxicity from high levels of [[methylmercury]] in swordfish.<ref name=\"Mercury Levels in Commercial Fish and Shellfish\">{{cite web\n|url=https://www.fda.gov/food/foodsafety/product-specificinformation/seafood/foodbornepathogenscontaminants/methylmercury/ucm115644.htm\n|title=Mercury Levels in Commercial Fish and Shellfish\n|author=FDA\n|date=1990\u20132010\n|accessdate=2011-09-14}}\n</ref><ref name=\"What you need to know about mercury in fish and shellfish\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.epa.gov/waterscience/fishadvice/advice.html#isthere\n|title=What you need to know about mercury in fish and shellfish\n|author=EPA\n|accessdate=2011-09-14}}\n</ref> The FDA recommends that young children, pregnant women, and women of child-bearing age not eat swordfish.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fda.gov/media/102331/download|title=Advice About Eating Fish|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=2019-09-27|author=FDA|publisher=[[FDA]]}}</ref>\n\nThe flesh of some swordfish can acquire an orange tint, reportedly from their diet of shrimp or other prey. Such fish are sold as \"pumpkin swordfish\", and command a premium over their whitish counterparts.<!-- (Information from U.S. vendor [[Whole Foods Market|Whole Foods]].)-->\n\nSwordfish is a particularly popular fish for cooking. Since swordfish are large, meat is usually sold as steaks, which are often [[grilled]]. Swordfish meat is relatively firm, and can be cooked in ways more fragile types of fish cannot (such as over a grill on skewers). The color of the flesh varies by diet, with fish caught on the East Coast of [[North America]] often being rosier.\n\n== Conservation status ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2011}}\n[[File:Xiphias gladius.jpg|thumb|Swordfish on deck during long-lining operations]]\nIn 1998, the US [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and [[SeaWeb]] hired [[Fenton Communications]] to conduct an advertising campaign to promote their assertion that the swordfish population was in danger due to its popularity as a restaurant entree.<ref>[http://www.fenton.com/pages/3_ourwork/4_casestudies/environment/swordfish.htm Swordfish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231113316/http://www.fenton.com/pages/3_ourwork/4_casestudies/environment/swordfish.htm |date=2007-12-31 }} Fenton Communications</ref>\n\nThe resulting \"Give Swordfish a Break\" promotion was wildly successful, with 750 prominent US chefs agreeing to remove North Atlantic swordfish from their menus, and also persuaded many supermarkets and consumers across the country.\n\nThe advertising campaign was repeated by the national media in hundreds of print and broadcast stories, as well as extensive regional coverage. It earned the [[Silver Anvil award]] from the Public Relations Society of America, as well as'' Time'' magazine's award for the top five environmental stories of 1998.\n\nSubsequently, the US [[National Marine Fisheries Service]] proposed a swordfish protection plan that incorporated the campaign's policy suggestions. [[President of the United States of America|Then-US President]] [[Bill Clinton]] called for a ban on the sale and import of swordfish and in a landmark decision by the federal government, {{convert|132670|sqmi|km2|abbr=on}} of the Atlantic Ocean were placed off-limits to fishing as recommended by the sponsors.\n\nIn the North Atlantic, the swordfish stock is fully rebuilt, with biomass estimates currently 5% above the target level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/fishwatch/species/n_atl_swordfish.htm|title=FishWatch}}</ref> No robust stock assessments for swordfish in the northwestern Pacific or South Atlantic have been made, and data concerning stock status in these regions are lacking. These stocks are considered unknown and a moderate conservation concern. The southwestern Pacific stock is a moderate concern due to model uncertainty, increasing catches, and declining [[catch per unit effort]]. Overfishing is likely occurring in the Indian Ocean, and fishing mortality exceeds the maximum recommended level in the Mediterranean, thus these stocks are considered of high conservation concern.<ref>[http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/content/media/MBA_SeafoodWatch_SwordfishReport.pdf Seafood Watch \u2013 Seafood Report \u2013 Swordfish] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714231946/http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/content/media/MBA_SeafoodWatch_SwordfishReport.pdf |date=2007-07-14 }} Monterey Bay Aquarium, 16 July 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Greenpeace International]] added the swordfish to its seafood red list.<!-- \"The Greenpeace International seafood red list is a list of fish that are commonly sold in supermarkets around the world, and which have a very high risk of being sourced from unsustainable fisheries.\"--><ref>{{cite web|title=Greenpeace International Seafood Red List|url=http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/campaigns/oceans/seafood/red-list-of-species/|accessdate=14 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==In culture==\n*The swordfish (''Xiphias'') has been used by astronomers as another name for the constellation of [[Dorado]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n== Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=Swordfish: A Biography of the Ocean Gladiator |author=Richard Ellis |year=2013 |isbn=978-0226922904}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Xiphiidae}}\n{{Wikispecies|Xiphias gladius}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070714231946/http://www.mbayaq.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/content/media/MBA_SeafoodWatch_SwordfishReport.pdf Swordfish, Seafood Watch, Monterey Bay Aquarium]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050420075231/https://www.fda.gov/fdac/reprints/mercury.html FDA Consumer:Mercury In Fish:Cause For Concern?]\n\n{{billfish|state=autocollapse}}\n{{commercial fish topics|start=autocollapse}}\n{{Meat|state=autocollapse}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q164327}}\n\n[[Category:Xiphiidae| ]]\n[[Category:Cosmopolitan fish]]\n[[Category:Oily fish]]\n[[Category:Sport fish]]\n[[Category:Hawaiian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Greek cuisine]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1758]]\n[[Category:Extant Pliocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n", "name_user": "174.21.146.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eDescription)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swordfish"}
{"title_page": "Katten Muchin Rosenman", "text_new": "{{external links|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Law Firm\n| firm_name = Katten Muchin Rosenman LLP (Katten)\n| firm_logo = [[File:Rebrand_Katten_Logo.png]]\n| headquarters = 525 West Monroe Street Chicago, IL 60661\n| num_offices = 11\n| num_attorneys = 700 (2020)<ref>{{cite web|title=Katten - Chicago - Law Firm Profile - Chambers USA 2020  - Chambers and Partners|url=https://chambers.com/law-firm/katten-usa-5:3629|website=www.chambersandpartners.com|publisher=Chambers & Partners|accessdate=30 January 2020|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n| key_people = Roger P. Furey, Chairman, Noah Heller, Chief Executive Officer<ref>{{cite web|title=D.C.-based partner moves up at Katten|url=http://www.chicagolawbulletin.com/archives/2016/05/24/katten-d-c-leader-5-24-16|website=Chicago Daily Law Bulletin|publisher=Law Bulletin Media|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref>\n| revenue = $635 million (2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2019 Am Law 100 Ranked by: Gross Revenue {{!}} The American Lawyer|url=https://www.law.com/americanlawyer/2019/04/23/the-2019-am-law-100-gross-revenue/|website=The American Lawyer|publisher=ALM Media Properties, LLC|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n| company_type = [[Limited liability partnership]]\n| homepage = [http://www.katten.com/ www.katten.com]\n}}\n\n'''Katten Muchin Rosenman LLP''' (Katten) is a full-service [[law firm]] with nearly 700 attorneys in locations across the United States and in London and Shanghai. The firm's core areas of practice include commercial finance, corporate, financial markets and funds, insolvency and restructuring, intellectual property, litigation, real estate, structured finance and securitization, transactional tax planning, and private wealth. Katten represents public and private companies in numerous industries, as well as a number of government and nonprofit organizations and individuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chambers.com/law-firm/katten-usa-5:3629|title=Katten, USA {{!}} Chambers Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=Chambers|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe firm was formed in 2002 through the merger of [[Chicago]]-based [[Katten Muchin & Zavis]] (founded in 1974) and [[New York City]]-based [[Rosenman & Colin]] (founded in 1912).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/about|title=About|website=katten.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings and Recognition==\nKatten is regularly honored for its diversity and women's programs<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile of Professional Organization Contributors Katten Muchin Rosenman, LLP|url= http://www.natlawreview.com/organization/katten-muchin-rosenman-llp| publisher=The National Law Forum, LLC |work=The National Law Review |date=2012-11-19|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> by legal publications such as MultiCultural Law Magazine,<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 Law Firms for Diversity|url=http://www.multiculturallaw.com/top100.pdf|publisher=L.P. Green & Partners, Inc.|work=MultiCultural Law|date=2012-06-19|accessdate=2012-12-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124011627/http://www.multiculturallaw.com/top100.pdf|archivedate=2013-01-24}}</ref> mainstream publications such as Working Mother magazine <ref>{{cite web |title= 2012 Working Mother 100 Best Companies |url=http://www.workingmother.com/best-companies/2012-working-mother-100-best-companies | publisher=Bonnier Corporation |work=Working Mother Media |date=2012-07-17|accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref> and by business groups such as the [[National Association for Female Executives]] \"NAFE\" rankings of Top 50 Companies for Executive Women.<ref>{{cite web |title=2012 NAFE Top 50 Companies for Executive Women |url=http://www.workingmother.com/best-company-list/122869/721 | publisher=Working Mother Media |work=Working Mother Magazine|date=2012-06-15|accessdate=2012-12-18}}</ref> Katten has been named one of the \u201cBest Places to Work for LGBT Equality\u201d by the Human Rights Campaign every year since 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrc.org/apps/buyersguide/profile.php?orgid=1587 |website=Human Rights Campaign |title=Buyers Guide |publisher=The Human Rights Campaign |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> and by Equality Illinois as one of the top Illinois law firms for LGBT inclusiveness and equality every year since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.equalityillinois.us/about-us/press-releases/raising-the-bar-2017/|title=Raising the Bar 2017 \u00ab Equality Illinois|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> The firm has been recognized by the Leadership Council on Legal Diversity (LCLD) as a Top Performer and recipient of the Compass Award in 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lcldnet.org/media/uploads/resource/2019_Recognition_List_V2.pdf|title=2019 Recognition List|last=|first=|date=|website=Leadership Council on Legal Diversity|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKatten has been certified for meeting the standards of the Mansfield Rule 2.0,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diversitylab.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Mansfield-2.0-and-3.0-Press-Release-FINAL-2.pdf|title=Mansfield-2.0-and-3.0-Press-Release-Final-2|last=|first=|date=September 3, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which directs law firms to consider at least 30 percent women, LGBTQ+ and minority attorneys for significant leadership roles. The Mansfield Rule, a winning idea from the 2016 Women in Law Hackathon hosted by Diversity Lab in collaboration with Bloomberg Law and Stanford Law School, was inspired by the NFL's Rooney Rule, which requires NFL teams to interview at least one minority candidate for head coach vacancies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diversitylab.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Mansfield-Rule-Legal-Department-Pilot-Press-Release-For-Distribution-April-4-2019-.pdf|title=Mansfield-Rule-Legal-Department-Pilot-Press-Release-For-Distribution-April-4-2019|last=|first=|date=April 4, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The rule was named after Arabella Mansfield, the first woman admitted to practice law in the United States. The firm is currently participating in the third version of the Mansfield Rule, which broadens the candidate pool to add attorneys with disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/katten-recognized-for-making-strides-towards-more-diversity-and-inclusion|title=Katten Recognized for Making Strides Towards More Diversity and Inclusion|website=katten.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\nKatten's attorneys and practices have been ranked in the BTI Litigation Outlook, Chambers Global, Chambers USA, Chambers UK, The Legal 500 United States, The Legal 500 United Kingdom and US News \u2013 Best Lawyers<sup>\u00ae</sup> \u201cBest Law Firms.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/webfiles/Katten_Awards_and_Rankings.pdf|title=Katten_Awards_and_Rankings|last=|first=|date=December 4, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 2018 as a top-tier Honor Roll firm in the areas of IP Litigation, Class Actions, Securities and Finance Litigation, and Complex Employment Litigation.<ref>{{cite web |title=BTI Litigation Outlook 2018: Changes, Trends and Opportunities for Law Firms |url=https://www.bticonsulting.com/publications/bti-litigation-outlook-2018-changes-trends-and-opportunities-for-law-firms |website=BTI Consulting Group |publisher=The BTI Consulting Group |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> The firm's [[Trusts and Estates]] practice has been recognized as an industry leader in the ''[[Chambers & Partners|Chambers High Net Worth]]'' 2017 guide for top talent and cross-border excellence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chambersandpartners.com/guide/hnw/21|title=The HNW Guide\u2019s Best lawyers and Law Firms|website=Chambers and Partners|publisher=Chambers & Partners|language=en-gb|accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nKatten has been highly ranked for US ABS/MBS Securitizations and CLO Underwriting Counsel. The firm was ranked second place for a fourth year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/katten-advances-in-underwriter-league-table-in-2019-us-abs-mbs-securitization-counsel-mid-year-rankings|title=Katten Advances in Underwriter League Table in 2019 US ABS/MBS Securitization Counsel Mid-Year Rankings|website=katten.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> among the most active issuers' counsel for US asset-backed and mortgage-backed securitizations and is in the top 10 of underwriters' counsel for US asset-backed and mortgage-backed securitizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Asset-Backed Alert :: Law Firms |url=https://www.abalert.com/rankings.pl?Q=107 |website=www.abalert.com |publisher=Harrison Scott Publications |accessdate=7 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Its [[Commercial Finance]] practice was named one of the top 10 dealmakers of 2017 and 2018 by Franchise Times, advising on more than 75 deals annually in the franchise and restaurant space, with loan sizes ranging from $25 million to more than $800 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Plus 9 more scrappy dealmakers  - Franchise Times - April 2018 - FranchiseTimes.com |url=http://www.franchisetimes.com/April-2018/Plus-9-more-scrappy-dealmakers/ |website=www.franchisetimes.com |publisher=Franchise Times |accessdate=7 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Katten has been recognized for its trademark services by World Trademark Review 1000 \u2013 The World's Leading Trademark Professionals (WTR 1000).<ref>{{cite web |title=United States: Illinois - Rankings - WTR 1000 - World Trademark Review |url=http://www.worldtrademarkreview.com/wtr1000/Rankings/Detail.aspx?g=002c8d08-cb9e-41c7-8012-c4679f0c4c38 |website=World Trademark Review |publisher=Globe Business Media Group |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> The firm's Sports and Sports Facilities practice was selected as a \u201cgo-to\u201d firm for Sports Law in Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dalton |first1=Brian |title=The Loop Elite: The Go-To Firms Of Chicago |url=https://abovethelaw.com/2017/07/the-loop-elite-the-go-to-firms-of-chicago/ |website=Above the Law |publisher=Breaking Media, Inc. |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Attorneys and Alumni==\n* Special Master of the US Court of Federal Claims - Brian H. Corcoran former Katten partner<ref>{{cite web |title=Brian H. Corcoran {{!}} US Court of Federal Claims |url=https://www.uscfc.uscourts.gov/brian-h-corcoran |website=www.uscfc.uscourts.gov |accessdate=27 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* On June 1, 2011, former [[Mayor of Chicago]] [[Richard M. Daley]] joined Katten Muchin Rosenman as [[of counsel]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Daley takes job at law firm that got city work |date=2011-06-01 |first1= Hal |last1=Dardick |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-06-01/news/ct-met-daley-law-job-20110601_1_chicago-skyway-and-parking-daley-law-firm}}</ref>\n* Former US District Chief of the Northern District of Texas - Judge Jorge Solis of counsel<ref>{{cite web |title=Katten Muchin adds former federal chief judge, four lawyers in Dallas |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/news/2018/05/11/katten-muchin-adds-former-federal-chief-judge-four.html |website=www.bizjournals.com |publisher=American City Business Journals |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>\n* US Magistrate Judge - M. David Weisman former Katten partner<ref>{{cite web |title=Emotions run high as judge sworn in |url=https://www.chicagolawbulletin.com/archives/2016/07/15/fed-mag-judge-weisman-7-15-15 |website=www.chicagolawbulletin.com |publisher=Law Bulletin Media |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Joshua D. Wayser \u2013 former Katten partner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/728492/calif-gov-taps-mofo-arnold-katten-partners-for-bench|title=Calif. Gov. Taps MoFo, Arnold, Katten Partners For Bench - Law360|website=www.law360.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n*Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Steve Cochran \u2013 former Katten partner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/981497/katten-muchin-cotchett-attys-among-34-new-calif-judges|title=Katten Muchin, Cotchett Attys Among 34 New Calif. Judges - Law360|website=www.law360.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n*In March 2018, Steven Reisman joined Katten as partner and head of the New York [[Insolvency]] and [[Restructuring]] practice.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Drake\u2019s Favorite Lawyer\u2019 and 4 More Move to Katten Muchin|url=https://www.law.com/americanlawyer/2018/03/26/drakes-favorite-lawyer-and-four-more-move-to-katten-muchin/?slreturn=20180722181244|website=www.law.com |publisher=The American Lawyer |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Reisman, who previously served as conflicts counsel during the historic [[bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers]] in 2008 and represented the [[Air Transportation Stabilization Board]] in the aftermath of [[9/11]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile: Reisman Tries His Luck at Katten|url=https://pipeline.thedeal.com/article/14686314/index.dl|website=www.thedeal.com |publisher=The Deal |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> has been profiled in various media as a \"celebrity lawyer\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Here\u2019s Proof That Drake And Kendrick Lamar Might Have Been In The Studio Together|url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/03/drake-and-kendrick-lamar-studio-collaboration/|website=www.vibe.com |publisher=Vibe |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> for his connections to the music industry.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Two Dollar Steve\u2019 Reisman Joins Katten Muchin|url=https://biglawbusiness.com/two-dollar-steve-reisman-joins-katten-muchin/|website=www.biglawbusiness.com |publisher=Bloomberg Law |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Who Is Steven Reisman? Meet Hip-Hop VIPs' Favorite Lawyer, the Man With the $2 Bills|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2014/02/steven-reisman-hip-hop-rap-lawyer-two-dollar-bills|website=www.complex.com |publisher=Complex |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.katten.com}}\n*[http://www.natlawreview.com/organization/katten-muchin-rosenman-llp The National Law Review profile]\n\n[[Category:Law firms based in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Law firms established in 2002]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-law-firm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{external links|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Law Firm\n| firm_name = Katten Muchin Rosenman LLP (Katten)\n| firm_logo = [[File:Rebrand_Katten_Logo.png]]\n| headquarters = 525 West Monroe Street Chicago, IL 60661\n| num_offices = 11\n| num_attorneys = 700 (2020)<ref>{{cite web|title=Katten - Chicago - Law Firm Profile - Chambers USA 2020  - Chambers and Partners|url=https://chambers.com/law-firm/katten-usa-5:3629|website=www.chambersandpartners.com|publisher=Chambers & Partners|accessdate=30 January 2020|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n| key_people = Roger P. Furey, Chairman, Noah Heller, Chief Executive Officer<ref>{{cite web|title=D.C.-based partner moves up at Katten|url=http://www.chicagolawbulletin.com/archives/2016/05/24/katten-d-c-leader-5-24-16|website=Chicago Daily Law Bulletin|publisher=Law Bulletin Media|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref>\n| revenue = $635 million (2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2019 Am Law 100 Ranked by: Gross Revenue {{!}} The American Lawyer|url=https://www.law.com/americanlawyer/2019/04/23/the-2019-am-law-100-gross-revenue/|website=The American Lawyer|publisher=ALM Media Properties, LLC|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n| company_type = [[Limited liability partnership]]\n| homepage = [http://www.katten.com/ www.katten.com]\n}}\n\n'''Katten Muchin Rosenman LLP''' (Katten) is a full-service [[law firm]] with nearly 700 attorneys in locations across the United States and in London and Shanghai. The firm\u2019s core areas of practice include commercial finance, corporate, financial markets and funds, insolvency and restructuring, intellectual property, litigation, real estate, structured finance and securitization, transactional tax planning, and private wealth. Katten represents public and private companies in numerous industries, as well as a number of government and nonprofit organizations and individuals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chambers.com/law-firm/katten-usa-5:3629|title=Katten, USA {{!}} Chambers Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=Chambers|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe firm was formed in 2002 through the merger of [[Chicago]]-based [[Katten Muchin & Zavis]] (founded in 1974) and [[New York City]]-based [[Rosenman & Colin]] (founded in 1912).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/about|title=About|website=katten.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings and Recognition==\nKatten is regularly honored for its diversity and women's programs<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile of Professional Organization Contributors Katten Muchin Rosenman, LLP|url= http://www.natlawreview.com/organization/katten-muchin-rosenman-llp| publisher=The National Law Forum, LLC |work=The National Law Review |date=2012-11-19|accessdate=2013-01-05}}</ref> by legal publications such as MultiCultural Law Magazine,<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 Law Firms for Diversity|url=http://www.multiculturallaw.com/top100.pdf|publisher=L.P. Green & Partners, Inc.|work=MultiCultural Law|date=2012-06-19|accessdate=2012-12-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124011627/http://www.multiculturallaw.com/top100.pdf|archivedate=2013-01-24}}</ref> mainstream publications such as Working Mother magazine <ref>{{cite web |title= 2012 Working Mother 100 Best Companies |url=http://www.workingmother.com/best-companies/2012-working-mother-100-best-companies | publisher=Bonnier Corporation |work=Working Mother Media |date=2012-07-17|accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref> and by business groups such as the [[National Association for Female Executives]] \"NAFE\" rankings of Top 50 Companies for Executive Women.<ref>{{cite web |title=2012 NAFE Top 50 Companies for Executive Women |url=http://www.workingmother.com/best-company-list/122869/721 | publisher=Working Mother Media |work=Working Mother Magazine|date=2012-06-15|accessdate=2012-12-18}}</ref> Katten has been named one of the \u201cBest Places to Work for LGBT Equality\u201d by the Human Rights Campaign every year since 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrc.org/apps/buyersguide/profile.php?orgid=1587 |website=Human Rights Campaign |title=Buyers Guide |publisher=The Human Rights Campaign |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> and by Equality Illinois as one of the top Illinois law firms for LGBT inclusiveness and equality every year since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.equalityillinois.us/about-us/press-releases/raising-the-bar-2017/|title=Raising the Bar 2017 \u00ab Equality Illinois|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> The firm has been recognized by the Leadership Council on Legal Diversity (LCLD) as a Top Performer and recipient of the Compass Award in 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lcldnet.org/media/uploads/resource/2019_Recognition_List_V2.pdf|title=2019 Recognition List|last=|first=|date=|website=Leadership Council on Legal Diversity|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKatten has been certified for meeting the standards of the Mansfield Rule 2.0,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diversitylab.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Mansfield-2.0-and-3.0-Press-Release-FINAL-2.pdf|title=Mansfield-2.0-and-3.0-Press-Release-Final-2|last=|first=|date=September 3, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which directs law firms to consider at least 30 percent women, LGBTQ+ and minority attorneys for significant leadership roles. The Mansfield Rule, a winning idea from the 2016 Women in Law Hackathon hosted by Diversity Lab in collaboration with Bloomberg Law and Stanford Law School, was inspired by the NFL's Rooney Rule, which requires NFL teams to interview at least one minority candidate for head coach vacancies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diversitylab.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Mansfield-Rule-Legal-Department-Pilot-Press-Release-For-Distribution-April-4-2019-.pdf|title=Mansfield-Rule-Legal-Department-Pilot-Press-Release-For-Distribution-April-4-2019|last=|first=|date=April 4, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The rule was named after Arabella Mansfield, the first woman admitted to practice law in the United States. The firm is currently participating in the third version of the Mansfield Rule, which broadens the candidate pool to add attorneys with disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/katten-recognized-for-making-strides-towards-more-diversity-and-inclusion|title=Katten Recognized for Making Strides Towards More Diversity and Inclusion|website=katten.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\nKatten's attorneys and practices have been ranked in the BTI Litigation Outlook, Chambers Global, Chambers USA, Chambers UK, The Legal 500 United States, The Legal 500 United Kingdom and US News \u2013 Best Lawyers<sup>\u00ae</sup> \u201cBest Law Firms.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/webfiles/Katten_Awards_and_Rankings.pdf|title=Katten_Awards_and_Rankings|last=|first=|date=December 4, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> 2018 as a top-tier Honor Roll firm in the areas of IP Litigation, Class Actions, Securities and Finance Litigation, and Complex Employment Litigation.<ref>{{cite web |title=BTI Litigation Outlook 2018: Changes, Trends and Opportunities for Law Firms |url=https://www.bticonsulting.com/publications/bti-litigation-outlook-2018-changes-trends-and-opportunities-for-law-firms |website=BTI Consulting Group |publisher=The BTI Consulting Group |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> The firm\u2019s [[Trusts and Estates]] practice has been recognized as an industry leader in the ''[[Chambers & Partners|Chambers High Net Worth]]'' 2017 guide for top talent and cross-border excellence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chambersandpartners.com/guide/hnw/21|title=The HNW Guide\u2019s Best lawyers and Law Firms|website=Chambers and Partners|publisher=Chambers & Partners|language=en-gb|accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nKatten has been highly ranked for US ABS/MBS Securitizations and CLO Underwriting Counsel. The firm was ranked second place for a fourth year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://katten.com/katten-advances-in-underwriter-league-table-in-2019-us-abs-mbs-securitization-counsel-mid-year-rankings|title=Katten Advances in Underwriter League Table in 2019 US ABS/MBS Securitization Counsel Mid-Year Rankings|website=katten.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> among the most active issuers' counsel for US asset-backed and mortgage-backed securitizations and is in the top 10 of underwriters' counsel for US asset-backed and mortgage-backed securitizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Asset-Backed Alert :: Law Firms |url=https://www.abalert.com/rankings.pl?Q=107 |website=www.abalert.com |publisher=Harrison Scott Publications |accessdate=7 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Its [[Commercial Finance]] practice was named one of the top 10 dealmakers of 2017 and 2018 by Franchise Times, advising on more than 75 deals annually in the franchise and restaurant space, with loan sizes ranging from $25 million to more than $800 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Plus 9 more scrappy dealmakers  - Franchise Times - April 2018 - FranchiseTimes.com |url=http://www.franchisetimes.com/April-2018/Plus-9-more-scrappy-dealmakers/ |website=www.franchisetimes.com |publisher=Franchise Times |accessdate=7 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Katten has been recognized for its trademark services by World Trademark Review 1000 \u2013 The World's Leading Trademark Professionals (WTR 1000).<ref>{{cite web |title=United States: Illinois - Rankings - WTR 1000 - World Trademark Review |url=http://www.worldtrademarkreview.com/wtr1000/Rankings/Detail.aspx?g=002c8d08-cb9e-41c7-8012-c4679f0c4c38 |website=World Trademark Review |publisher=Globe Business Media Group |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> The firm\u2019s Sports and Sports Facilities practice was selected as a \u201cgo-to\u201d firm for Sports Law in Chicago.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dalton |first1=Brian |title=The Loop Elite: The Go-To Firms Of Chicago |url=https://abovethelaw.com/2017/07/the-loop-elite-the-go-to-firms-of-chicago/ |website=Above the Law |publisher=Breaking Media, Inc. |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Attorneys and Alumni==\n* Special Master of the US Court of Federal Claims - Brian H. Corcoran former Katten partner<ref>{{cite web |title=Brian H. Corcoran {{!}} US Court of Federal Claims |url=https://www.uscfc.uscourts.gov/brian-h-corcoran |website=www.uscfc.uscourts.gov |accessdate=27 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* On June 1, 2011, former [[Mayor of Chicago]] [[Richard M. Daley]] joined Katten Muchin Rosenman as [[of counsel]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Daley takes job at law firm that got city work |date=2011-06-01 |first1= Hal |last1=Dardick |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2011-06-01/news/ct-met-daley-law-job-20110601_1_chicago-skyway-and-parking-daley-law-firm}}</ref>\n* Former US District Chief of the Northern District of Texas - Judge Jorge Solis of counsel<ref>{{cite web |title=Katten Muchin adds former federal chief judge, four lawyers in Dallas |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/news/2018/05/11/katten-muchin-adds-former-federal-chief-judge-four.html |website=www.bizjournals.com |publisher=American City Business Journals |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>\n* US Magistrate Judge - M. David Weisman former Katten partner<ref>{{cite web |title=Emotions run high as judge sworn in |url=https://www.chicagolawbulletin.com/archives/2016/07/15/fed-mag-judge-weisman-7-15-15 |website=www.chicagolawbulletin.com |publisher=Law Bulletin Media |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>\n* Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Joshua D. Wayser \u2013 former Katten partner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/728492/calif-gov-taps-mofo-arnold-katten-partners-for-bench|title=Calif. Gov. Taps MoFo, Arnold, Katten Partners For Bench - Law360|website=www.law360.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n*Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Steve Cochran \u2013 former Katten partner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/981497/katten-muchin-cotchett-attys-among-34-new-calif-judges|title=Katten Muchin, Cotchett Attys Among 34 New Calif. Judges - Law360|website=www.law360.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n*In March 2018, Steven Reisman joined Katten as partner and head of the New York [[Insolvency]] and [[Restructuring]] practice.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Drake\u2019s Favorite Lawyer\u2019 and 4 More Move to Katten Muchin|url=https://www.law.com/americanlawyer/2018/03/26/drakes-favorite-lawyer-and-four-more-move-to-katten-muchin/?slreturn=20180722181244|website=www.law.com |publisher=The American Lawyer |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> Reisman, who previously served as conflicts counsel during the historic [[bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers]] in 2008 and represented the [[Air Transportation Stabilization Board]] in the aftermath of [[9/11]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile: Reisman Tries His Luck at Katten|url=https://pipeline.thedeal.com/article/14686314/index.dl|website=www.thedeal.com |publisher=The Deal |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> has been profiled in various media as a \"celebrity lawyer\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Here\u2019s Proof That Drake And Kendrick Lamar Might Have Been In The Studio Together|url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/03/drake-and-kendrick-lamar-studio-collaboration/|website=www.vibe.com